05386nam a22009255i 9780520972285DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2020017888  a97805209722857 a10.1525/97805209722852doi  a(DE-B1597)566318  a(OCoLC)1198930106  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aU167.5.H86bG67 2020 4aU167.5.H86bG67 2020 7aPOL0350102bisacsh04a355.4/222231 aGordon, Neve, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHuman Shields :bA History of People in the Line of Fire /cNicola Perugini, Neve Gordon. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2020  a1 online resource (312 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tIntroduction -- t1. Civil War -- t2. Irregulars -- t3. Settlers -- t4. Reports -- t5. Peace Army -- t6. Emblem -- t7. Nuremberg -- t8. Codification -- t9. People's War -- t10. Environment -- t11. Resistance -- t12. Humanitarian Crimes -- t13. Manuals -- t14. Scale -- t15. Hospitals -- t16. Proximity -- t17. Info-War -- t18. Posthuman Shielding -- t19. Women and Children -- t20. Spectacle -- t21. Computer Games -- t22. Protest -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom Syrian civilians locked in iron cages to veterans joining peaceful indigenous water protectors at the Standing Rock Sioux Reservation, from Sri Lanka to Iraq and from Yemen to the United States, human beings have been used as shields for protection, coercion, or deterrence. Over the past decade, human shields have also appeared with increasing frequency in antinuclear struggles, civil and environmental protests, and even computer games. The phenomenon, however, is by no means a new one. Describing the use of human shields in key historical and contemporary moments across the globe, Neve Gordon and Nicola Perugini demonstrate how the increasing weaponization of human beings has made the position of civilians trapped in theaters of violence more precarious and their lives more expendable. They show how the law facilitates the use of lethal violence against vulnerable people while portraying it as humane, but they also reveal how people can and do use their own vulnerability to resist violence and denounce forms of dehumanization. Ultimately, Human Shields unsettles our common ethical assumptions about violence and the law and urges us to imagine entirely new forms of humane politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aHuman shieldxHistory. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Human Rights.2bisacsh  aAmerican Civil War.  abody.  acivilian.  acoercion.  adehumanization.  aenable.  aenvironmental.  agenealogy.  aglobal middle east.  ahistory.  ahuman.  ainternational.  alaw.  amilitary target.  aphenomenon.  apolitics.  aprotection.  aprotest.  arefugees.  aresistance.  arestraint.  aviolence.  aweaponize.1 aPerugini, Nicola, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDTL Humanities 2020z978311073776908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2020z9783110704594oZDB-23-PLW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2020 Englishz978311070472308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press Frontlist eBook-Package 2020z978311069041540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/97805209722